  "meta": {
    "title": "Antarctic Ice Algae: Phaeocystis and the Krill-Larvae Race",
    "date": "2026-07-24",
    "lesson": "In the Southern Ocean, platelet ice on the underside of Antarctic fast ice hosts dense mats of the colonial haptophyte Phaeocystis antarctica alongside diatoms, all held together by copious exopolysaccharide (EPS) mucus that they secrete to survive brine-channel freezing and buffer against ice crystal damage. This sticky, carbohydrate-rich matrix is what makes ice algae edible and defensible at once: it slows heterotrophic bacteria digging in, but also becomes their main carbon source once released into the water column during the spring melt, fueling a short, frantic food pulse that overwintering krill larvae depend on. The cold (around -1.8C at the ice-water interface) keeps every metabolic rate depressed (Q10 effects), so growth, grazing and division are all slow and patient rather than frantic, and particles persist far longer than in temperate seas. Because the habitat is physically confined to a thin brine-channel skin, nutrients are locally rich but spatially trapped -- a colony that does not commit to EPS anchoring gets torn off into the water column and lost.",
    "citation": "Arrigo & Thomas 2004, Antarctic Science; Krembs et al. 2002, Deep-Sea Research II (EPS in sea ice)",
    "difficulty": "hard",
    "realWorldBasis": "Antarctic land-fast sea ice, platelet ice layer, McMurdo Sound, Phaeocystis antarctica / diatom community"
  },
